eqislife - I agree. But this is very similar to how MUDs have always worked.  And there are probably thousands of MUDs (most go down in a month), only a handful survive.  It is very difficult to make a popular MUD.  If it isnt the players that give you problems, it will be a slew of bonehead GMs running twink MUDs  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"> <P>What I liked about working with MUDs was the programming.  Some people liked creating cool zones. Others liked writing AI scripts, etc.  The problem is balancing the MUD and making it popular.<P>NWN sounds like it will have many small worlds where only friends hang out together doing campaigns.  That is fun for a while, its even more fun if you can manage to get 50 people on your server.  But in reality the novelty wears off  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0">  After all, if its only 9 of my friends playing in my world, why wouldnt we just get together in RL hehe.<P>What sets apart games like NWM and MMORPGs is that an MMORPG will allow people to meet that probably wouldnt be possible in RL (due to distances etc).  We have all met players from all over the world (back since the MUD days), and this is cool.
</FONT>
