<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
/em is a NWN fanboy.<P>TheWarrior:  I believe your points have merit.  NWN is very much like an old Mud.  Although there are some key elements that might separate it.  The graphics at first glance are quite nice.  Sure the novelty might wear off over time and become "just a MUD."  I've seen the dungeon/campaign tool in action and it was pretty amazing how quickly you could put together a map.  I haven't seen the scripting wizards yet, so not sure what the impact might be.  But the promise is that their wizards will accelerate the time it takes to put together quests and such.<P>The other key element that gets me all worked up are the portals.  The ability to link together an unlimited number of servers opens up some serious possibilities for a collection of serious world creaters.  The common number thrown around is about 64 players per server are possible.  I feel I should point out this number is based primarily on the bandwidth of the typical DSL/Cable connection a person might have.  The engine itself is capable of handling more and requires a surprisingly wimpy machine to pull it off.  So in theory (yeah, I'm dreaming) a number of people spread out over the globe could organize (even loosly), link their machines, and create a much larger virtual world (if they could all agree on the the rules of play -- the dreaming part  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"> ).<P>I will grab this game at first opportunity.  I will create a "home base" for my characters on my own server and grow my own little world from there.  My hope is to find other like minded folks out there that I can link to and maybe, eventually, grow to something more grand.<P>/em is a dreamer.<P>--------------------<P> <IMG SRC="http://www.kansas.net/~brian/sig.jpg"> 
</FONT>
