<BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>Originally posted by Gravelgut:<BR><STRONG>I don't know how others feel, but NWN sounds like it might actually work.  Sure, you can cheat and get a high level character quickly, but it doesn't amount to much.  The challenge is what is fun.  If I can get the challenge, I will be happy to stay level one for weeks or months.<P>The challenge is what I found lacking in EQ.  There doesn't seem to be much of a middle ground.<P>One concern:  Is death a problem?  If death carries little penalty, like EQ, then some of the challenge is gone.  If it carries a big penaly, how do you deal with GM's who create killer worlds?</STRONG><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P><BR>Unless you go through great pains to cheat your character will lose his "offical" status. I don't think cheating will be as big as an issue in this game compared to current mmorpgs. This game will lack the competitive drive in current mmorpgs for the following reasons.<P>1. No one really to compete against. This is due to the fact that there will only be 64 players tops with you at any one time (average games will be like 6-8). <P>2. Unlimited resources. There will be no camping, ksing, and uber weapons will all be unique ( I think they said there billons of possiable combinations (yep billons)(yep DM's get to make weapons to)).<P>3. More role-playing and story driven then current hack and slash rpg's. Good DMs will, hopefully through good story telling, make the lower levels just as interesting as the higher ones. So no rush. Alot of the current games don't get interesting till higher up so people rush to get there.<P>4. The fact that anyone can do it is also a deterrent. It won't impress anyone and you won't feel "uber". I think uber will move from who has the best gear and most time to who is the best role-player and storyteller. Thats something not everyone can do well.<P>Moving on, death is handled<BR>different ways. The DM sets up how he wants it in his world. The basic way it handled is this you drop to 0 your KO. You then will slowly start losing hps till you hit -10 at which point you will die unless someone intervens (via potion spell etc). If you die what happens then is dependant on the DMs rules.
