<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
I will like it too.  Not for the graphics, or eaven the role-playing, but because it will not be simple rote.<P>One of the problems with EQ-style games is that the content is basically static, with little new content added.  What randomness there is is isolated to small instances, and the repetition becomes scripted.  Changes require months of coding by skilled professional coders.<P>NWN is similar to many business systems I have helped design.  It is a data driven system, where the basic toolset is an interface allowing you to change the data.  This allows for fast flexible changes.<P>It is also very hard to develop, taking usually three times longer than a statically coded system.  The payoff is in changes later, which take virtually no time.  As long as the meta-information system is well designed, the system wil rock.  <P>With hundreds of designers out there, great systems will result.  Here is my next question...<P>According to the NWN folks, they will not charge a monthly fee.  I can see some GM's becoming in great demand as their skills and creativity become well known.  Everyone will clamor to be part of their world.  Will NWN complain when those GM's start charging for access to their worlds?  <P>Imagine, I create a world, and everyone likes it.  Now, I can only GM so much in my 'free' time, so I decide that if people want to play in my world, they will have to pay.  I charge, say $5.00 per player per night.  A group of 30 players play each night, 5 nights a eek.  I make $750.00 per week, or $3,000 per month, running the game.<P>Will NWN management mind?  (I really believe it will happen.)<P>--------------------<P>Josef - Servant of Balance
</FONT>
<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
